<subSubSection box="[199,1180,871,897]" pageId="21" pageNumber="402" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,151,1041]" box="[199,1180,871,897]" pageId="21" pageNumber="402">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,871,897]" pageId="21" pageNumber="402">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named after the brown transverse band dorsally on the face.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="402" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,151,1041]" pageId="21" pageNumber="402">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,907,933]" pageId="21" pageNumber="402">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species superficially resembles other species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1934" box="[911,1056,907,933]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hecaloidella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="402" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[911,1056,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="402">Hecaloidella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but is only tentatively included in the genus as the anterior margin of the vertex is more evenly rounded in dorsal view, it lacks the distinctly convex face in profile (
<figureCitation box="[321,408,979,1005]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[180,1412,192,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-19@20.[176,1412,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 9. H. brunifasciata; A–B, habitus, dorsal and lateral view; C, face; D, head and thorax, anterior view; E, male pygofer and anal tube, lateral view; F–G, male Xth segment, lateral and caudal view; H, style; I, connective, dorsal view; J, aedeagus, caudal view; K, valve and subgenital plates, dorsal view; L, aedeagus and connective, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629122" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629122/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="402">Fig. 9B</figureCitation>
); the antennae arise slightly higher on the face (
<figureCitation box="[937,1023,979,1005]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[180,1412,192,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-19@20.[176,1412,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 9. H. brunifasciata; A–B, habitus, dorsal and lateral view; C, face; D, head and thorax, anterior view; E, male pygofer and anal tube, lateral view; F–G, male Xth segment, lateral and caudal view; H, style; I, connective, dorsal view; J, aedeagus, caudal view; K, valve and subgenital plates, dorsal view; L, aedeagus and connective, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629122" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629122/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="402">Fig. 9C</figureCitation>
) and the male segment X is extended ventrally (
<figureCitation box="[266,398,1015,1041]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[180,1412,192,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-19@20.[176,1412,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 9. H. brunifasciata; A–B, habitus, dorsal and lateral view; C, face; D, head and thorax, anterior view; E, male pygofer and anal tube, lateral view; F–G, male Xth segment, lateral and caudal view; H, style; I, connective, dorsal view; J, aedeagus, caudal view; K, valve and subgenital plates, dorsal view; L, aedeagus and connective, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4629122" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4629122/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="402">Figs. 9F–G</figureCitation>
). It is also significantly larger than other species of the genus.
</paragraph>
